article.headline: Williams scores 20, adds 11 boards
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- Phoenix Mercury coach John Shumate knew his team was better than its 2-11 record. On Saturday night, his players proved him right. Adrian Williams had a career-high 20 points and 11 rebounds as the Mercury ended the Detroit Shock's eight-game winning streak with a 68-65 victory. "This is the way that these women have played all season," said Shumate, a former Detroit Piston. "We've been 90-percent of the way to these wins several times, but we haven't been able to finish them off. Tonight, we did that." The Mercury won for the first time in seven road games this season -- 24 hours after losing at Minnesota. "This feels very good," said Kayte Christensen, who scored 11 points. "We knew we could beat good teams -- we've come close before -- but now we've earned some respect. For some reason, we match up really well with that team." Detroit also was playing for the second consecutive night, having won Friday in New York. The defeat was the first for the Shock since opening night. "We weren't going to go 31-1," Shock coach Bill Laimbeer said. "We knew this was coming -- we just didn't expect it tonight. The key will be how we respond to losing." Deanna Nolan led Detroit with 14 points and Swin Cash added 12. But Cash missed two free throws in the final minute and was just 4-of-9 from the line in the game. "This is disappointing, especially to a team we felt we should have beaten," Cash said. "You have to give a lot of credit to Phoenix, but we didn't match their intensity level. We let them get a lot of confidence." Cheryl Ford added eight points and 10 rebounds for Detroit. Phoenix led 35-28 at the half behind 16 points from Williams, but the Shock scored the first six points of the second half to cut the margin to one. Christensen, though, scored seven points in just over five minutes to move the Phoenix lead to 44-37 with 14 minutes to play. The Mercury led by as many as 10 in the final 10 minutes, and were still up 64-57 with four minutes to go. Ford scored four points in a 6-0 run that pulled Detroit within 64-63 with 2:19 left. After the teams traded baskets, Cash rebounded a miss by Tamicha Jackson and was fouled. But she missed both free throws. Jackson missed again with 25 seconds to go, and Ford grabbed the rebound to give Detroit another chance. But Kedra Holland-Corn missed a 3-pointer, and Ford couldn't save the rebound. Edwina Brown, who was traded from Detroit to Phoenix before the season, made two free throws to make it 68-65, and Elaine Powell missed a 3 at the buzzer. "I'm just glad we could beat anyone -- we needed this," Brown said. "It felt weird to play here -- this was my second home for three years, and I spent a lot of time working with the same players that I was playing against tonight."

Game notes
Former Shock coach Nancy Lieberman was in the stands, along with Detroit Pistons draft choice Darko Milicic. ... Three members of the Phoenix rotation -- Brown, Anna DeForge and Jackson -- are former Detroit players. ... Williams hit all seven of her field-goal attempts in the first half.
